msgid "Container orchestration"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: containers-orchestration.xml:15
#, no-c-format
msgid "Pod deployment with &podman;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-orchestration.xml:17
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In addition to building and managing images, &podman; makes it possible to "
"work with pods. A pod is a group of one or more containers with shared "
"resources, such as the network interface. A pod usually encapsulates an "
"application composed of multiple containers into a single unit."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-orchestration.xml:24
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <command>podman pod</command> can be used to create, delete, query, and "
"inspect pods. To create a new pod, run the <command>podman pod create</"
"command> command. This creates a pod with a random name. To list the "
"existing pods, use the <command>podman pod list</command> command. To view a "
"list of running pods, run <command>podman ps -a --pod</command> . The output "
"of the command looks as follows (the <literal>STATUS</literal> and "
"<literal>CREATED</literal> columns are omitted for brevity):"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: containers-orchestration.xml:34
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"POD ID        NAME                # OF CONTAINERS   INFRA ID\n"
"399a120a09ff  suspicious_curie    1                 e57820093817\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-orchestration.xml:38
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Notice that the command assigned a random name to the pod "
"( <literal>suspicious_curie</literal> in this case). You can use the "
"<parameter>--name</parameter> parameter to assign the desired name to a pod."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-orchestration.xml:44
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To examine the pod and its contents, run the <command>podman ps -a --pod</"
"command> command and take a look at the output (the <literal>COMMAND</"
"literal> , <literal>CREATED</literal> , <literal>STATUS</literal> , "
"<literal>PORTS</literal> , and <literal>POD ID</literal> columns are omitted "
"for brevity)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: containers-orchestration.xml:52
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"CONTAINER ID  IMAGE                 NAMES              PODNAME\n"
"e57820093817  k8s.gcr.io/pause:3.2  399a120a09ff-infra suspicious_curie\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-orchestration.xml:56
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The created pod has an <literal>infra</literal> container identified by the "
"<filename>k8s.gcr.io</filename> name. The purpose of this container is to "
"reserve the namespaces associated with the pod and allow &podman; to add "
"other containers to the pod."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-orchestration.xml:63
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Using the <command>podman run --pod</command> command, you can run a "
"container and add it to the desired pod. For example, the command below runs "
"a container based on the <literal>suse/sle15</literal> image and adds the "
"container to the <filename>suspicious_curie</filename> pod:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: containers-orchestration.xml:70
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"podman run -d --pod suspicious_curie registry.suse.com/suse/sle15 sleep 1h"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-orchestration.xml:72
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The command above adds a container that sleeps for 60 minutes and then "
"exits. Run the <command>podman ps -a --pod</command> again, and you should "
"see that the pod now has two containers."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-orchestration.xml:78
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Containers in a pod can be restarted, stopped, and started without affecting "
"the overall status of the pod. For example, you can stop a container using "
"the <command>sudo podman stop <replaceable>CONTAINER_NAME</replaceable></"
"command> command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-orchestration.xml:85
#, no-c-format
msgid "To stop the pod, use the <command>podman pod stop</command> command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: containers-orchestration.xml:89
#, no-c-format
msgid "podman pod stop suspicious_curie"
msgstr ""
